# The big picture

**Our mission and focus is to help democratic institutions keep pace with a rapidly changing world.** This is the shared glue that unites all of our projects, initiatives, and staff together — people may be working on different projects, with different tech stacks, in different countries, at different time scales, but it all comes back to this. 

The POPVOX Foundation team views global legislatures as a fulcrum for policy and process evolution with influence on all branches and levels of democratic governance. We see democratic legislatures as deeply interconnected, where trends, events, and innovations impacting one will have ripple effects around the world. We believe that modernized legislatures can “lift all boats” with more informed policymaking, increased public engagement, and transparent, trustworthy processes. This not only means investing in technology and continuous learning but also fostering a governance structure that remains resilient and informed in the age of AI and other exponential technologies. 

POPVOX Foundation engages with international and U.S.-based legislatures through a four-pronged approach: 

* Providing cooperative assistance  
* Exerting constructive external pressure   
* Facilitating institutional knowledge sharing and networking, and  
* De-risking technology projects through prototypes, open source development and technical assistance 

Through informal advising, expert testimonies, training sessions, publications, and informal dialogues, the team aids Congress and other legislatures in their own evolutions. Simultaneously, by identifying deficiencies, highlighting improvements, and celebrating significant advancements, POPVOX Foundation helps maintain a momentum of positive change and encourages the onward, ongoing march of modernization.

# How we work

## Team culture

**Meta-goals**: Beyond the content of our individual projects, the impact we aim to have in our larger ecosystem is…

* Demonstrating the value of an approach to government modernization that starts from a long-term vision of what’s possible, balancing championing existing good work on the inside with respectful, within-reach calls for accountability where appropriate.  
* Empowering people who are best-informed on how government can work and informing those already in power to support positive, substantive movement toward governments that work better for everyone.  
* Prioritizing collaboration and convening within the ecosystem of other organizations in our space.   
* Building a strong pipeline of talented, tech-savvy people from diverse backgrounds into the modernizing-government world, and empowering/elevating new voices to make an impact on government reform.  
* Keeping good people in our world by building a sustainable work culture that gets things done for the long haul. 

**Positive and creative approaches to change**: We embrace a broad toolkit to move toward a government that works better for everyone, but always with realistic optimism and positivity. In practice, this means…

* We aim to counterbalance the coverage and scholarship of Congress that focuses on chaos and gloom. We believe in the institution, with a full appreciation of its flaws, and aim to champion a positive vision for what it can be.  
* Where possible, we highlight success stories and applaud great work happening inside and outside government globally. Where accountability is needed, we aim to make it as easy as possible for stakeholders to do the right thing.  
* We deliberately experiment with new methods to drive change, starting from the needs of staff, constituents, stakeholders, and our team.

**Focusing on the institutional, not the political:** While team members are all individuals with their own opinions and priorities about political topics, POPVOX Foundation is nonpartisan and apolitical. 

* Our work centers on institutional, technocratic questions; not policy or elections.   
* Our effectiveness is directly linked to maintaining a reputation for working for the good of the institution, not any particular party or agenda.   
* We welcome productive conflict, but we don’t pick fights that don’t advance our work.

**Flat and agile**: Our key to success is finding smart people and giving them room to run. This means that…

* Overall direction and strategy are collaboratively across the whole team, with the Executive Director and Managing Director responsible for executing on strategy by coordinating team projects.  
* To the extent possible, we aim to prioritize projects that move the ball forward without tying up our limited capacity in indefinite commitments. For example, we may explore an open-source proof-of-concept tech project without committing to long-term service delivery. In general, our projects have off-ramps or are umbrella initiatives with flexibility.  
* Staff and fellows are empowered to pick up opportunities and run with them, managing their own bandwidth and capacity as needed (in consultation with the leadership team).  
* Where we may run into challenges with our limited capacity, the leadership team will work with staff and fellows on project scope, scale, and timing with a view to the overall scope of Foundation work and priorities.

**Defining success**: Key to being an agile organization that is able to pivot to capitalize on opportunities is building in flexibility with how we define success. Some starting points include…

* Each staff member and fellow is expected to define success for their own portfolio/project, in consultation with the leadership team.   
* We fully expect and encourage staff and fellows to be flexible and constantly re-evaluate the best ways to define and measure success.  
* In general, our team leans away from quantitative metrics: while defined KPIs like events per quarter may make sense in some contexts and for some projects, we want to lean away from defined quantifiable metrics and toward narrative/observed impact when measuring the Foundation’s success as a whole.

**Shared consciousness**: Key to running a collaborative, agile organization is building a shared understanding of the full context and development of our work. This means that we…

* Default to open \+ transparent internally: e.g. public Slack channels, open calendars, cc’s and bcc’s.  
* Default to asynchronous updates: where possible, trying for virtual updates to free up team members’ calendars.  
* Set full-team meetings and 1:1s deliberately to build shared consciousness and relationships while preserving productive time.

## A note on partisanship

As we discussed in your interview(s), we understand that each of us comes to the Foundation with our own set of political beliefs and preferences. However, we focus on the long-term health and stability of our system of government: fundamental to our work at the Foundation is our ability to be on the side of the institution over the parties that work in it. 

That includes being careful in our individual, personal social media accounts to maintain a reputation that will not automatically turn off potential partners and stakeholders from either side of the aisle.

# Talking about our work

Sometimes it can be difficult to explain who we are and what we do — we combine a lot of different elements, and may need to explain or emphasize different parts of our work in different contexts. Here is a starting point to familiarize yourself with to introduce our work to new audiences.

**POPVOX Foundation Elevator Pitch**  
Overview: **POPVOX Foundation is a nonpartisan 501(c)(3) dedicated to helping legislatures keep pace with rapid technological and societal change**. We work globally — supporting Congress, state legislatures, and parliaments worldwide — to build government capacity and improve the feedback loops that make democratic institutions more effective, resilient, and responsive.

Key Talking Points:

* Nonpartisan 501(c)(3) working to strengthen democratic institutions  
* Global and multilevel scope – supporting Congress, state legislatures, and democratically-elected parliaments worldwide  
* The Legislative Pacing Problem (flagship concept) – the gap between the pace of technological and societal change and the capacity of legislative institutions to keep up

Specific areas of work:

* Interbranch Feedback Loop – improving how information and insights flow between the legislative, executive, and judicial branches, and between government and constituents  
* Congressional/Legislative Modernization – helping democratic legislatures adopt better technology, processes, and practices  
* Building Government Capacity – supporting legislative staff and federal workforce with tools, resources, and professional development  
* Practical Solutions – we create both tools (StaffLink, CRSBot, Case Compass) and convene stakeholders to solve shared challenges  
* Constituent Connection – strengthening how representatives understand and respond to community needs

## Slack

* To be clear, **no one is ever expected to read everything that comes through Slack** :) Our team uses Slack as a communications platform but also a shared notebook to track updates, developments, writing, publications, etc related to our issue areas and portfolios. Feel free to read what is interesting and relevant to your work, and to rest easy letting the rest go.  
* Understanding that everyone is on different time zones and work schedules, there is no expectation that you will respond immediately. However, responding to team members within 1 business day is expected unless you’ve flagged longer periods when you’ll be unreachable in advance.  
* Our Slack channels fall into a few categories, and there are a few in particular to note:  
  * **Project channels:** these are working channels for us to coordinate, collaborate, and build the record on our specific projects. For example, \#casework-navigator, departure-dialogues, caribbean-dpp, new-member-orientation, etc.  
  * **Topic/news channels:** these are essentially a shared team notebook to capture news stories, academic papers, social media posts, etc related to a topic within our focus. Some of these are also helpful for gathering items to be included in our newsletters, e.g. \#casework-news and \#future-proofing-newsletter  
  * **Operational channels:**   
    * \#communications: project management for our communications team  
    * \#intern-team: management for our intern team, including dropping project suggestions and questions that you’d like to assign to an intern  
    * \#journo-outreach: managing our mentions in media outlets, journalist relationship-building, and prep for/debrief from interviews  
    * \#meetings-intel: internal-only (no interns/fellows) channel for sharing candid reports from meetings with internal/external stakeholders  
    * \#reviews: channel for managing almost-final work products through their final review and approval process. When you post a piece of work in reviews, please be clear on who you need it approved by, any questions you’d like your reviewers to keep an eye out for, and deadlines.  
    * \#shoutouts: our team is awesome, so say thank-you/congrats when it’s deserved\!  
    * \#website: for Juan to track and manage changes to the website. This does not include update/blog posts, but more site architecture, evergreen/who-we-are copy, etc.  
    * \#whereabouts: for flagging periods when you’ll be unavailable — please also keep your calendar up to date with OOO blocks, but this is helpful for giving long-term heads-ups and flagging shorter periods like doctor’s appointments  
* We’d strongly recommend using Slack’s channel-grouping tools to set up your Slack in a way that works well for you (e.g. Anne uses “priority projects,” “team logistics” “other projects,” “reading,” and “misc”).   
* For project-related communications, we default to posting in the appropriate Slack channel so it’s easy for everyone involved to follow along. For everything else, please feel free to DM anyone on the team.  
  * Threads are encouraged\!  
  * As are emojis :)

# Travel policy

# **POPVOX Foundation International Travel Security Policy**

## **Purpose**

This policy establishes guidelines for team member travel to foreign countries to ensure personnel safety, protect organizational data and intellectual property, protect the organizational data and security of our partners and collaborators, and maintain operational continuity while supporting our global work.

## **Scope**

This policy applies to all POPVOX Foundation employees, contractors, and fellows traveling internationally for organizational purposes or personal travel during employment.

## **Travel Classification System**

### **Prohibited Travel Destinations**

Travel to the following categories of countries is **prohibited** without written exception approved by the Executive Director:

* **Permanently prohibited**: Russia, China, Iran, North Korea  
* **U.S. State Department Level 4 (Do Not Travel)**: All countries on the current State Department Travel Advisory Level 4 list  
* **Active Conflict Zones**: Countries experiencing active military conflict or civil war  
* **High Kidnapping Risk**: Countries with demonstrated patterns of detaining or kidnapping foreign nationals for political purposes

### **High-Risk Destinations (Requires Advanced Approval)**

Travel to countries with the following characteristics requires **written approval at least 30 days in advance**:

* U.S. State Department Level 3 (Reconsider Travel) advisories  
* Countries with limited U.S. diplomatic presence or consular services  
* Regions with elevated terrorism risks  
* Countries with unpredictable enforcement of local laws affecting foreign nationals  
* Locations with significant infrastructure or health system challenges

**Approval Process**: Submit detailed itinerary, security plan, and business justification to Managing Director. Approval must include security protocols and emergency response plan.

### **Moderate-Risk Destinations and Standard Destinations (Notification Required)**

Travel to countries with Level 2 (Exercise Increased Caution) or Level 1 (Exercise Normal Precautions) advisories requires **notification at least 14 days in advance** to your direct supervisor and the Managing Director.

**Notification for Level 2 countries should include**: destination, dates, purpose, accommodation details, and local contact information.

**Notification for Level 1 countries should include:** destination, dates, purpose.

## **Organizational Partnership Travel**

### **Approved Partner Organizations**

POPVOX Foundation recognizes that travel with established international democracy and governance organizations provides additional security infrastructure, local expertise, and risk mitigation. Travel to **High-Risk Destinations** (Level 3\) may be approved through a streamlined process when organized by the following types of partner organizations:

**Pre-Approved Partner Categories:**

* **Any US government agencies:** State Department, Congress, White House, etc.  
* **Democracy Support Organizations**: National Democratic Institute (NDI), International Republican Institute (IRI), National Endowment for Democracy (NED)  
* **Legislative Strengthening Networks**: Westminster Foundation for Democracy (WFD), Agora Central Europe, International Institute for Democracy and Electoral Assistance (International IDEA), Afripal  
* **Multilateral Institutions**: Council of Europe, OECD, Organization of American States (OAS)  
* **Established Conferences**: World Forum for Democracy (Council of Europe), Afripal conferences, Inter-Parliamentary Union assemblies

**Additional partners may be approved by the Executive Director and added to this list based on:**

* Demonstrated security protocols and incident response capabilities  
* Track record of safe operations in challenging environments  
* Coordination with diplomatic missions and local authorities  
* Professional staff with regional expertise

### **Streamlined Approval Process for Partner Travel**

When traveling as part of an organized delegation or conference with approved partners to High-Risk (Level 3\) destinations:

**Notification Timeline**: **30 days advance notice** to Managing Director

**Required Information:**

1. Partner organization name and program/event details  
2. Complete itinerary including partner-provided accommodations and transportation  
3. Local U.S. Embassy/Consulate coordination (if applicable)  
4. Group emergency contact information  
5. Any partner-specific security briefings or requirements

**Approval Considerations:**

* Partner organization's security track record in the specific country  
* Current security situation vs. typical country advisory level  
* Timing relative to elections, protests, or other destabilizing events  
* Traveler's role and necessity of participation  
* Availability of alternative participation methods (virtual attendance)

### **Partner Travel Still Subject to Standard Requirements**

Even when traveling with approved partners:

* **Prohibited destinations remain prohibited** (Level 4, Russia, China, Iran, North Korea) without Executive Director exception  
* All pre-travel requirements apply (STEP registration, emergency contacts, travel insurance)  
* All electronic device security protocols apply  
* Check-in protocols apply (though may be coordinated through partner organization)  
* Post-travel reporting required

### **Partner Security Assessment**

For first-time travel with a new partner organization or to a new country with an existing partner, the following should be documented:

1. **Partner Security Briefing**: Request and review partner's security protocols  
2. **Local Coordination**: Confirm partner's relationships with local authorities and U.S. diplomatic presence  
3. **Medical Support**: Identify medical facilities and evacuation capabilities  
4. **Communication Plan**: Establish how to reach partner staff in emergencies  
5. **Group vs. Individual Time**: Understand when travelers will be in group vs. independent settings

## **Pre-Travel Requirements**

### **All International Travel**

1. **STEP Registration**: Enroll in the U.S. State Department's Smart Traveler Enrollment Program (STEP) at least 7 days before departure  
2. **Emergency Contacts**: Provide POPVOX Foundation with:  
   * Complete itinerary with dates, locations, and accommodations  
   * Local contact phone numbers  
   * Emergency contact information for family/next of kin  
   * Expected return date  
3. **Travel Insurance**: Verify international travel insurance coverage, including medical evacuation if traveling to high-risk destinations  
4. **Country Briefing**: Review current State Department Country Information and Travel Advisories

### **High-Risk Destination Travel (Additional Requirements)**

1. **Check-in Protocol**: Establish regular check-in schedule (daily or as determined by risk assessment)  
2. **Emergency Communication Plan**: Identify backup communication methods if primary channels fail  
3. **Local Support**: Identify local U.S. Embassy/Consulate locations and emergency contact numbers  
4. **Risk Assessment Review**: Document and acknowledge specific risks for the destination

## **Electronic Device Security Protocols**

### **General Principles**

* Assume all electronic communications may be monitored in foreign countries  
* Treat all devices as potentially compromised upon return  
* Minimize sensitive data carried on traveling devices

### **Pre-Departure Device Preparation**

**For all international travel:**

1. **Device Inventory**: Document all devices being taken (laptops, phones, tablets, USB drives)  
2. **Data Minimization**: Remove all non-essential sensitive data, documents, and files  
3. **Software Updates**: Ensure all operating systems and security software are current  
4. **Backup**: Complete full backup of devices before departure  
5. **Encryption**: Verify full-disk encryption is enabled on all devices  
6. **Password Strength**: Ensure strong, unique passwords/passphrases for all devices and accounts  
7. **Multi-Factor Authentication**: Consider using authentication apps rather than SMS

**For high-risk and prohibited destinations (if exception granted):**

1. **Clean Devices**: Use dedicated "travel devices" with minimal data and fresh installations  
2. **Separate Accounts**: Use travel-specific email and cloud storage accounts, not primary work accounts  
3. **VPN Configuration**: Install and test VPN before departure (note: VPNs may be illegal in some countries)  
4. **Disable Cloud Sync**: Turn off automatic cloud synchronization services  
5. **Consider Device Loan**: Request temporary devices that will be wiped upon return

### **During Travel**

1. **Physical Security**:

   * Never leave devices unattended in hotel rooms, vehicles, or public spaces  
   * Use hotel safes for device storage when not in use (acknowledge these are not highly secure)  
   * Keep devices as carry-on luggage; never check them  
2. **Network Security**:

   * Avoid public Wi-Fi networks; use cellular data or VPN  
   * Disable automatic Wi-Fi connection and Bluetooth when not in use  
   * Never use hotel business centers or public computers for sensitive work  
   * Assume hotel Wi-Fi networks are monitored  
3. **Communication Security**:

   * Use end-to-end encrypted messaging apps (Signal, WhatsApp) for sensitive communications  
   * Avoid discussing sensitive organizational matters on phone calls  
   * Be cautious of phishing attempts and social engineering  
4. **Border Crossings**:

   * Power down devices during border crossings  
   * Understand you may be required to provide access to devices  
   * Know your rights and organizational policy if access is demanded  
   * Document any device searches or demands for passwords/access  
5. **Suspicious Activity**:

   * Report any unusual device behavior immediately  
   * Report any attempts to install software or access your devices  
   * Report suspicious questioning about your work

### **Post-Travel Protocols**

**All international travel:**

1. Report any lost, stolen, or confiscated devices immediately  
2. Report any incidents requiring disclosure of passwords or device access  
3. Change passwords for all accounts accessed during travel  
4. Monitor accounts for unusual activity

**High-risk destinations:**

1. **Account Review**: Comprehensive review of account access logs  
2. **Debrief**: Complete security debrief documenting any concerning incidents

## **Check-In Protocols**

### **Standard Check-Ins**

* Team members should respond to organizational communications within reasonable time zones  
* Notify supervisor of any significant itinerary changes

### **Enhanced Check-Ins (High-Risk Travel)**

* Daily check-ins via agreed-upon method at specified times  
* Missed check-in triggers escalation protocol  
* Emergency contact notification if traveler becomes unreachable

## **Emergency Response**

### **If Detained, Arrested, or Questioned by Authorities**

1. Request to contact the U.S. Embassy or Consulate immediately  
2. Do not sign documents you don't understand  
3. Note names and badge numbers of authorities

### **If Devices Are Confiscated or Searched**

1. Do not attempt to prevent search if legally required  
2. Document what was searched/taken  
3. Report immediately to POPVOX Foundation  
4. Assume all data on device is compromised

### **Emergency Contact**

* **Primary**: Marci Harris 703-899-4306  
* **Secondary**: Anne Meeker 330-819-5998

## **Exceptions and Waivers**

Exceptions to this policy may be granted only by the Executive Director for:

* Critical organizational mission requirements  
* Extraordinary circumstances with adequate security measures

Exception requests must include:

* Detailed business justification  
* Comprehensive risk assessment  
* Enhanced security protocols  
* Emergency response plan

## **Personal Travel**

This policy applies to personal international travel during employment when:

* Travel is to prohibited or high-risk destinations  
* Travel could impact organizational security or operations  
* Team member has access to sensitive organizational data or systems

Team members should notify their supervisor of personal travel to high-risk destinations using the same notification timelines.

## **Training and Compliance**

* All team members will receive annual training on this policy  
* Violation of this policy may result in disciplinary action  
* Policy will be reviewed annually and updated as needed based on evolving threats

## **Resources**

* **U.S. State Department Travel Advisories**: travel.state.gov/travel  
* **STEP Registration**: step.state.gov  
* **Country Information**: travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/international-travel/International-Travel-Country-Information-Pages.html  
* **Emergency Services Abroad**: Embassy and consulate contact information

# **POPVOX Foundation Content Review Process Guide**

![][image1]

## **Core Principle: Content Owner Responsibility**

**The content owner is responsible for the entire lifecycle of their content piece from ideation through publication.** This includes:

* Having initial scoping conversations with team leaders  
* Moving content through each required stage  
* Running content through the style guide bot  
* Meeting deadlines  
* Posting in the reviews channel with complete context  
* Following up on pending reviews  
* Coordinating with Juan for formatting and publication

## **Getting Started: Scoping Conversation**

Before drafting, have a conversation with your team leader or in one of the standing team meetings:

* **Anne** for US team content  
* **Aubrey** for global team content

Discuss:

* What are you creating, and who is the audience/intended outcome?  
* Which tier does it fall into?  
* Where will it live? (website section, Substack, etc.)  
* Timeline and any deadline considerations

## **Content Tiers**

### **Tier 1: Flagship Research**

**High-profile, important research products from our team**

**Examples:**

* Flagship research reports \- Representative Bodies, FutureProofing Congress, American Ingenuity, etc.  
* Major policy publications \- NMO white paper, casework data white paper

**Review Process:**

1. Draft  
2. Run style guide bot  
3. Copyedit  
4. Team leader review (Anne or Aubrey)  
5. Post in reviews channel → Marci substantive review (content, tone, direction, coherence)  
6. Juan formats for web/print  
7. Marci final review on formatted version (may involve feedback loop with owner, Juan, and team leader)  
8. Publish

**Key Notes:**

* Marci reviews twice: once substantively before formatting, once for quality control after formatting  
* Highest level of scrutiny and polish

**Content representing POPVOX Foundation's institutional position**

**Examples:**

* Press releases  
* Blog posts in Foundation voice  
* Foundation updates  
* Congressional letters or commendations

**Review Process:**

1. Draft  
2. Run style guide bot  
3. Copyedit  
4. Team leader review (Anne or Aubrey)

# Network security guidelines

# **Network Security and Information Protection**

## **Purpose**

Our work at POPVOX Foundation connects us with Congressional staff, international parliaments, civil society organizations, and democracy reform partners worldwide. These relationships are built on trust, and protecting that trust is essential to our mission and effectiveness. This chapter provides guidance on recognizing and responding to situations where someone may be attempting to gain leverage, access our materials, or map our networks inappropriately.

## **Core Principles**

### **Trust Your Instincts**

**If a conversation feels weird, end it quickly.**

You don't need to justify or explain yourself. A simple "I need to run" or "Let me get back to you" is always acceptable. Your gut feeling is data—take it seriously. You're not being rude by protecting our work, and it's always okay to pause and consult with colleagues.

### **Understanding Trust Thresholds**

Different relationships in our network require different levels of caution when sharing information:

**Highest Trust: Current Congressional staff you know directly**

* Information passed directly from these relationships  
* Known, verified relationships with specific offices

**Moderate Trust: Known partners in the congressional modernization ecosystem**

* Established relationships with verified organizations (NDI, IRI, WFD, Council of Europe, etc.)  
* Regular collaborators with track records

**Lower Trust / Verify: Multiple degrees of separation**

* New contacts or cold outreach  
* Unverified connections claiming relationships with your network  
* People resurfacing unexpectedly after long periods

### **Stay in Your Lane**

Avoid commenting on issues or policies outside our scope of work. We're experts in congressional modernization, legislative capacity building, and democratic strengthening—not policy positions. Our expertise includes:

* How Congress works and how to improve it  
* Legislative processes and constituent engagement  
* Technology adoption in democratic institutions  
* Interbranch feedback loops and casework systems

When asked about topics outside our scope, politely redirect: "That's outside my area of expertise—you might want to reach out to \[appropriate organization/expert\]."

## **Protecting Information About Our Networks**

Be mindful when discussing certain types of information, even in seemingly casual conversations:

### **Congressional Relationships**

* **Which specific offices or Members we're working with**, especially on sensitive or emerging topics  
* **Congressional staff movements, hiring, or departures** unless staff have made this public themselves  
* **Internal deliberations or upcoming announcements** before they're public  
* **Details about which specific offices you're working with on particular issues**

### **Network Mapping**

Watch for questions that seem designed to map our network rather than understand our work:

* "Who else are you working with on this?"  
* "Which offices have you been talking to about this issue?"  
* "Can you introduce me to your contacts in \[office/committee\]?"

### **Partner Information**

* Avoid sharing details about partners' timelines, funding, or internal challenges  
* Don't discuss other organizations' relationships with Congressional offices  
* Be cautious about sharing information about partner staffing or strategic plans

### **For Congressional Staff Connections**

**Don't make introductions without checking with both parties first.** Even if both people are in your network, verify that both would want the connection before facilitating it. This protects everyone's time and maintains trust.

## **Recognizing Red Flags**

### **Suspicious Requests**

Be alert to requests that don't follow normal professional patterns:

* **"Just have a quick call" with no clear purpose or context** \- Professional requests typically include a clear agenda or reason  
* **Artificial urgency** \- "I need this today for a meeting tomorrow" when there's no obvious reason for the rush  
* **Bypassing normal channels** \- "Could you just send me X directly instead of going through \[normal process\]?"  
* **Odd specificity in questions** about processes, relationships, or access points that seems more detailed than the conversation warrants  
* **Claiming unverifiable relationships** \- "Your colleague said you'd be the perfect person to talk to about..." (verify these claims)

### **Social Engineering Tactics**

Watch for manipulative approaches designed to make you feel obligated or special:

* **Excessive flattery or ego appeals** \- "You're the expert, I really need your take on this..."  
* **Building personal rapport very quickly** \- Moving from professional to overly familiar too fast  
* **Creating a sense of obligation** \- Gifts, excessive praise, or unsolicited favors that make you feel like you "owe" them something  
* **Making interactions feel confidential** \- "This is just between us..." or "Don't mention this to \[colleague\]..."

### **Separation Tactics**

Be wary of attempts to separate you from your organization or team:

* **"This is just your personal view, right?"** \- Attempting to get unofficial or unvetted opinions that aren't POPVOX Foundation's position  
* **Discouraging you from consulting colleagues** \- "You don't need to check with anyone, you know this better than they do"  
* **Pressuring for immediate answers** \- Making you feel like you can't take time to think or consult with your team

Remember: It's always okay to consult with your team before sharing information or making commitments.

### **People Resurfacing Out of the Blue**

Be aware when old contacts suddenly reappear after months or years of no contact. This can be genuine reconnection—or can be someone targeting you with newfound knowledge about your current work.

Ask yourself:

* Why now? What prompted this outreach?  
* How did they know about my current work or role?  
* Are they asking unusually specific questions about what I'm working on?  
* Does this feel like genuine reconnection or information gathering?

If something feels off, trust that instinct.

## **The Five D's: Your Response Toolkit**

When you encounter a suspicious situation or need to buy time, use these strategies:

### **DELAY**

"Let me think about that and get back to you."

Use this when you need time to consider whether a request is appropriate, or to consult with colleagues.

### **DEFLECT**

"That's outside my area—you should contact \[appropriate person/office\]."

Use this to redirect questions that are outside your scope or that should go through official channels.

### **DEFER**

"I'd need to check with my team before sharing that."

Use this when you're not sure if information can be shared, or when it feels like the kind of thing that should involve your manager or colleagues.

### **DOCUMENT**

Note the interaction and mention it to your supervisor.

Keep a record of:

* Who contacted you and how (email, phone, social media, in person)  
* What they asked for or discussed  
* What felt unusual or concerning  
* Date, time, and any other relevant context

### **DISCUSS**

Quick heads-up to colleagues in Slack if something feels off.

Loop in the team in the \#meetings-intel channel or directly with your manager. The team will take it seriously and won't think you're overreacting. It's better to flag something that turns out to be fine than to miss something important.

## **Document and Report**

### **When to Document**

Document interactions when:

* Something feels off, even if you can't articulate exactly why  
* Someone asks unusual questions about our work, partners, or networks  
* You encounter any of the red flags listed above  
* Someone tries to bypass normal processes or channels  
* You're asked to keep a conversation confidential from your team

### **What to Document**

* Who contacted you and how they reached out  
* What they asked for or discussed  
* What specifically felt unusual or concerning  
* Date, time, and any other relevant context  
* Any follow-up they requested

### **Where to Report**

* **For immediate concerns or urgent situations**: Message your manager directly  
* **For general awareness**: Post in the \#meetings-intel channel (internal staff only)  
* **If you're uncomfortable approaching your manager**: Reach out to Anne, Marci, or Ben

You're not overreacting by documenting and reporting—you're protecting our team and our partners.

## **Best Practices**

### **General Awareness**

* Be thoughtful about what you share on social media about specific projects or partners  
* Use organizational email for first contacts rather than personal accounts  
* Be cautious about meetings in unusual locations or overly social settings early in a relationship  
* Notice if someone is trying to establish a sense of obligation through gifts, excessive praise, or unsolicited favors

### **Communication Hygiene**

* Default to organizational email for new professional contacts  
* Be cautious about adding people to group communications or shared workspaces without vetting  
* Verify identities before sharing Zoom links or calendar holds for sensitive discussions  
* Document unusual interactions or requests in the \#meetings-intel channel

### **Information Sharing**

* If you're not confident about whether information can be shared, ask your manager first  
* Never invent or guess at attributions—if you don't know something, say so  
* Be protective of Congressional staff contact information—even if public, don't aggregate or share lists  
* Remember that even public information can be sensitive when aggregated or contextualized

## **Remember: This Is Normal**

Most of the people you interact with are genuine, well-intentioned colleagues in the congressional modernization space. These guidelines aren't about being paranoid—they're about being **thoughtful and protective** of the trust our partners place in us.

By staying aware and looking out for each other, we strengthen our ability to do this work effectively and safely. Our position in the ecosystem is unique and valuable, which means we need to be mindful stewards of the relationships and information we're entrusted with.

**When in doubt, talk to your team. We've got your back.**

## **Questions or Concerns**

If you have questions about whether something is appropriate to share, or if you encounter a situation covered by these guidelines:

* **Your Manager \+ Anne**: First point of contact for most situations  
  * **Anne Meeker**: Managing Director \- 330-819-5998  
* **Marci Harris**: Executive Director  
* **Ben Harris**: For technical/IT security concerns

Don't hesitate to reach out. These guidelines exist to support you, and we'd much rather you ask than worry about whether you're handling something correctly.

# Media engagement

# **POPVOX Foundation Media Engagement Process**

## How we tell our story 

POPVOX Foundation is a unique organization in the nonprofit/think tank universe. The (fairly new) organization has evolved substantially since its founding in 2021, building on lessons learned by its founders from over a decade in civic technology *and* working directly with Congress as staffers, advisors, and observers. The team brings diverse backgrounds, ideologies, expertise and a common mission: “to help democratic institutions keep pace with a rapidly changing world..”

## Media Engagement Goals

Our media strategy is not just “coverage for coverage sake” but rather geared toward several goals:

* **Promote Our Mission, Policy Goals, and Experts:** Elevate our professional reputation as innovative thinkers who bring a new kind of tech savvy expertise to questions on democracy reform and government accountability. 

* **Deepen Journalist Relationships:** Provide timely assistance and educate journalists on our work, how we frame issues related to government reform and modernization, and allies who could also be useful sources.

* **Frame Media Coverage**: Raise awareness of the “pacing problem” and new concepts related to emerging technologies in government. While getting quoted is often ideal, it is more important to add substantive knowledge and inform journalists’ framing of democracy and governance issues than to earn a citation. 

* **Institutional Voice Consistency**: Represent the organization's voice in harmony with our established tone that supports positive, substantive movement toward a government that works better for everyone. We celebrate wins, praise noteworthy institutional efforts, and cheerlead progress. While we are not a watchdog, at times we may call government actors out on suboptimal policy decisions, while we articulate solutions.

* **Elevate New Voices**: Leverage our position to amplify others with underrepresented perspectives (e.g., women, BIPOC, center-right experts), from both within our organization and among key allies. 

* **Professional Development**: Support the continuous professional growth of our team, offering opportunities for media engagement skill enhancement.

## Media Policy

You can talk to the media on background (i.e., off the record), and will need to alert the Journo Outreach channel immediately afterwards. Before going on the record, you will need to coordinate with Comms. (Read “Handling Media Inquiries” below for more details.)

## Attribution Guidelines

Staff who are authorized to talk to the media and are acting in their official capacity to  
convey the official position or perspective of POPVOX Foundation should request that the reporter identify them by their title and affiliation to POPVOX Foundation. (e.g., This quote should be attributed to Marci Harris, cofounder and executive director of POPVOX Foundation. ***NB: Please let the reporter know there is no “The” before POPVOX Foundation and POPVOX is all-caps**.*)

Staff who are not acting in their official capacity, such as for volunteer work or personal  
interests, etc., should refrain from identifying themselves as POPVOX Foundation staff. (e.g., Gabriela Schneider, resident of North Kohala, Hawaii.)

## Handling Media Inquiries

* If a reporter contacts you for a story, respond right away to ensure we are interviewed before their deadline and before they move on to someone else. Tell the reporter that you are happy to help *on background* (this means you’re off the record), and want to ensure we share the right resources and expertise. Ask them:  
  * for their deadline;   
  * what angle they are taking on the story;   
  * who else they’re talking to;  
  * …**and let them know either you or someone else from POPVOX Foundation will be in touch very soon.**

* Send a note to the [Journo Outreach channel](https://app.slack.com/client/T01QR0UPRFV/C05VC2XFZ3M) (tagging Gab), sharing details about the story, reporter, their contact info, outlet, and deadline (if you know). If you do not believe you have the expertise (or bandwidth) to talk to the reporter, please suggest other sources you’d recommend.   
  * Note: If the inquiry is on deadline that same day before noon EST/1 PM EDT, please also tag Marci and Anne.

* Gab will confer with the team on top points to accentuate, any related resources we should highlight to the reporter, and the appropriate messenger.   
  * Note: There may be times when it would make sense to redirect the reporter to a colleague who might be the best person to respond, especially as we strive to elevate more voices in our space.

* If the deadline is urgent, the selected spokesperson will contact the reporter directly to respond to their inquiry. If we have more time, feel free to tag Gab in the Journo Outreach Slack thread so she can help schedule the chat.  
    
* Before the interview, Gab will chat with the spokesperson to provide guidance and review talking points.

* Once the spokesperson has finished the interview, they will send a note to the Journo Outreach channel (tagging Gab) sharing how it went and if there are any specific follow-up needs (e.g., good resources of ours or from our allies to share).

* Gab will follow up with the reporter with links to resources, to learn when the story might go live, and to deepen our rapport.

## Once We’re Cited 

* Gab (or the staff quoted if they get a link first) shares to the General and/or Communications Slack channel, as well as any relevant issue area and/or newsletter channels (e.g., to include in a future Future-Proofing Congress ).  
* Juan shares the article on social media.  
* Gab saves the citation in our [spreadsheet](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/10l-NffQ7CfAIHkSGjj__0mBuomXsV8LKxEXXYuLsgfQ/edit#gid=0), noting date, outlet, author, topic, staff quoted, and quote. Gab also uploads a PDF of the article in this [folder](https://drive.google.com/drive/u/0/folders/18xOvNbXkJhGOjepGpCf1FvJLLY14aqaC) (in case of link rot), and verifies that we have the most up-to-date contact information in our press list.  
* If we placed an op-ed, Juan cross-posts to our blog, linking to and citing the original.

## General Best Practices for Media Interviews

The reporter reached out because of our subject matter expertise, but an interview is not a data dump. You can be discerning with what you share. To be helpful doesn’t necessarily mean answering every question. Together, we’ll craft talking points with intentional choices about what you are going to say with these goals in mind:

* What would be the perfect headline?  
* What is the number one thing you want readers to know?  
* What are three things that you want to say to ensure that readers are hearing that number one thing?

Guidelines for developing core messages:

1. Develop up to three short phrases, 7‐10 words each, that each encapsulate your core message. Keep them simple.  
2. Avoid trying to memorize a long sentence or paragraph. Focus on a few key phrases that help you express the point. This helps you sound natural.  
3. Metaphors or analogies are often the best way to do this.  
4. Use vivid, interesting, or catchy language.  
5. Appealing to your audience’s values or aspirations rather than merely reciting data is more persuasive.  
6. Always avoid jargon.  
7. Remember — you may be talking with a reporter but they are not the audience. Your audience is the readers/listeners. Your sound bites should resonate with them.  
8. If appropriate, try to use humor (not sarcasm) to illustrate your point. (***Never use sarcasm; it doesn’t translate well.***)

It is also a good idea to consider what the worst headline would be and to make sure that none of your talking points could possibly take you there. Additionally, it’s a great general practice to offer other sources to amplify underrepresented voices and help the reporter connect with allies.

**During the interview**  
If you’re doing the interview over the phone/video, have your notes handy. It’s also helpful to have a glass of water nearby (and a lozenge if you have a cough). Remember to breathe and take your time. As you speak, smiling translates well and also elevates your mood. Importantly, always assume that ***everything you say is on the record***, even during the opening chit chat before what seems like the “official” interview begins.

There are a few key things to remember during the interview:

* It is perfectly reasonable to ask a reporter to repeat their question. Sometimes questions are unclear and you need clarification. Other times, you just need a moment to consider your answer.  
* If a reporter asks you a complex, multi‐part question, answer the one part of that question that leads you back to the core message that you want to deliver.  
* This is an interview, not a conversation.  
* It may feel odd but you do not have to answer direct questions. You can pivot back to your on top messages. For example, you might say, “I think to understand this issue, the key point to remember is...\[insert your talking point.\]”    
* A more advanced version is to use a keyword in the question as your pivot. For example if the reporter asks, “What did you have for breakfast?” You can respond, “As I was having breakfast today, I was thinking about…\[insert your talking point\].”  
* Keep your cool. Give calm and balanced answers and focus on presenting yourself as a confident, reasonable person.  
* Speak reasonably slowly. If you hear a reporter scribbling notes, slow down and let them catch up. It might feel odd, but it is okay to repeat a sound bite.  
* When in doubt, it’s good to consider whether what you’ll say:   
  * Is true?  
  * Is on message?  
  * Is helpful?  
  * Bonus points: Is kind?

## Developing Media Narratives

Gab is always on the search for new story ideas and reasons to persuade reporters to interview our experts with our framing of an issue, and is happy to collaborate with you on pitches. Please feel free to bring these ideas up in our team meetings or send a message to the Journo Outreach Slack channel, tagging Gab.

***What is a pitch?*** It’s a vehicle for grabbing a reporter's (or editor’s or podcaster’s) attention to influence how they cover stories related to our mission. Most pitches will be brief emails highlighting a new report, coalition letter, policy explainer, etc. with a key spokesperson identified to entice the writer/podcaster to interview them on our behalf. 

Sometimes, Gab will send a more formal statement related to a developing story in the news and/or legislative cycle that includes a quote that can be copy/pasted into a story and a plug to interview that spokesperson. (And yes, reporters do sometimes copy quotes from pitches\!) This is a particularly helpful tactic for rapid response. If there is breaking news that we have a good angle on, please send a note to the Journo Outreach Slack channel and tag Gab (as well as Marci and Anne if it is before noon EST or 1 PM EDT. *If it’s early and super important, feel free to text Gab in case Slack notifications are still paused*.)

When we have advanced knowledge of the publication of an important government report, substantive policy enactment, or formal guidance to be issued, please give Gab a heads up so we can craft a pitch that will arrive in time to maximize our ability to ride that news wave. (Even better if we can share that news in an embargoed way so the reporter can pre-interview and have the story land with a citation as the news breaks.)

***What is embargoed information?*** That’s when we are authorized to share privileged information (like the adoption of a new policy) before it happens, with an agreement that the reporter won’t publish the information until a predetermined time that we set. We can likewise share our own embargoed information, particularly when pitching an exclusive on a report or other POPVOX Foundation resource. (Gab will share a copy of such resource with a watermark that says “Embargoed Draft” with the reporter.)

### Speaking of the adoption of new policies…

If we are working with a Member or committee who will adopt a new policy that they intend on promoting to the media, always offer to provide a validating quote. Send a note to the Communications Slack channel and tag Gab, and she’ll follow up with you to craft the quote and accompanying social media promotional language together. Be sure to ask the Member’s Comms Director if you can connect them to Gab so we can collaborate on what specific keywords or points to amplify and learn their deadline.

## Questions?

Let me know if there’s something not covered or if you have any questions on the above. Thank you for all you do to raise awareness about POPVOX Foundation and our work\!

# Background reading

## Helpful background reading

Joining a new team can be overwhelming. If you have time before you get started, here are some helpful things to take a look at:

Not-us:

* **House Select Committee on the Modernization of Congress**: the Select Committee (aka “ModCom”) was a temporary committee created in the 116th Congress to look at how to make Congress work better. This committee did incredible work to model bipartisan cooperation, and create lasting change in the House. Many of the committee’s recommendations have already been implemented, and more are now being moved forward by the newly-created Committee on House Administration Subcommittee on Congressional Modernization. Our team worked closely with ModCom over the last several years, including testifying several times. We would strongly recommend browsing the Committee’s [hearings](https://www.youtube.com/@selectcommitteeonthemodern9383/videos), and reading through the [final report](https://www.congress.gov/117/crpt/CRPT-117hrpt646/GPO-CRPT-117hrpt646.pdf).   
* Recoding America

Our work:

* The [POPVOX.org](http://POPVOX.org) website: One of the best ways to learn about all that POPVOX Foundation does and has done\! It is also an invaluable way to learn about *how* we talk about the work that we do, our tone, attitude, and scope of work. Subscribe to our newsletters and take the time to explore every page, project, and initiative.   
* Our [back catalog](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/10l-NffQ7CfAIHkSGjj__0mBuomXsV8LKxEXXYuLsgfQ/edit?gid=765296179#gid=765296179) of media hits: this is a helpful introduction to how others write about us and our work, and the expectations for commenting to the media.
